-- French Stocks Advance; Arkema, Danone, Hermes, Korian Shares Move in Paris
-- B y   A l e x i s   X y d i a s
-- 2010-11-09T17:03:54Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-09/altarea-devoteam-psb-korian-novagali-safetic-french-equity-preview.html
France’s  CAC 40 Index  rose 0.8
percent to 3,945.71 at the 5:35 p.m. close in Paris, while the
SBF 120 Index gained 0.9 percent.  The following stocks rose or fell in the French equity
market. Company symbols are in parentheses.       Arkema SA  (AKE FP) jumped 3.4 percent to 49.35 euros, the
highest level since July 2007. The chemical maker spun off from
Total SA raised its annual earnings forecast for the third time
in 2010 as growth in Asia, an acquisition and price increases
boosted third-quarter sales 41 percent.       CGGVeritas  (GA FP) jumped 7.9 percent to 20.05 euros, the
best performance in the SBF 120. Chief Executive Officer  Jean- Georges Malcor  said he hopes to achieve full-year consensus
estimates for 2010 after the world’s largest seismic surveyor of
oilfields unexpectedly reported a third-quarter net loss.  Danone  (BN FP) rose 1.5 percent to 47.16 euros. Japanese
companies are interested in Danone’s bottled-water business,
including the Evian brand, the Wall Street Journal reported on
its website, citing unidentified people familiar with the
matter.  Sabrina Schneider, a spokeswoman for Paris-based Danone,
declined to comment on the Journal report.  Hermes International SCA  (RMS FP) jumped 7.6 percent to
166.05 euros. The luxury-goods maker in which LVMH Moet Hennessy
Louis Vuitton SA holds a stake raised its full-year revenue
forecast after third-quarter sales jumped 31 percent.  Korian  (KORI FP) gained 1 percent to 17 euros, the first
advance in six days. The retirement-home operator raised its
sales forecast for the year and now predicts 8 percent growth.
Third-quarter revenue climbed 9.8 percent to 237.6 million euros
($329 million).  SafeTIC  (ALEGR FP) slumped 7.4 percent to 6.11 euros, the
worst performance since May. The maker of security
identification systems said it will seek to raise as much as 6.7
million euros in a private placement, selling shares at 5.60
euros each. The company confirmed its estimates for the year and
said third-quarter revenue rose 35 percent.  Societe Internationale de Plantations d’Heveas SA  (SIPH FP)
added 2.2 percent to 92.1 euros, the highest close since at
least 1991. The rubber producer said third-quarter sales rose 94
percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
